div.p:
Two inscribed boundary markers found in the area of Bragylai (mod. Metallikon in Greece) attest to the restoration of boundaries by a proconsul of Macedonia, one P. Clodius Capito Aurelianus. One text was first published in the 1970’s (Text 

               29.1 (Elliott 2004)
         ). The other is unpublished (see Hatzopoulos 1989, 58 n. 1).  The boundaries, between Bragylai and two other communities whose locations are unknown to us (Tiberioi and Kissynioi), were restored on the basis of a boundary demarcation (otherwise unknown and not extant) of a “King Philip,” who is not more explicitly identified. If the guess that Aurelianus was serving under Trajan or Hadrian is correct, this would mean he consulted and followed evidence that could have been over 400 years old.
